                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.51ForcedLoan,1926/2: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-01-25T15:00:00+02:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 25, 1926—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 25—1:34 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. My 6, January 24, 3 p.m. Commercial attaché has telegraphed his Department
                    fully with request to give you copy.</p>
                <p>Spanish Minister<note n="16" xml:id="d203fn16">Cristobal Fernandez Vallin, dean
                        of the diplomatic corps.</note> informs me that he and those of his
                    colleagues whose countries have had treaties explicitly exempting their
                    nationals from forced loans are jointly protesting accordingly.</p>
                <p>I have as yet received no communication from Foreign Office on the subject, but I
                    addressed a formal note to Minister for Foreign Affairs this morning, making
                    provisional reservations against application to American citizens so as to
                    permit whatever action you may instruct me to take.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
